why use logisitic Regression:
       Logistic regression is used when the dependent variable is categorical,
as it models probabilities using the sigmoid function and ensures outputs lie between 0 and 1.
Basically predict outcome based on true or false

What Logistic Regression Actually Does

👉 Step 1: Calculate a linear combination(it means Multiply inputs by weights and add them up)
👉 Step 2: Pass it through sigmoid(sigmoid converts any number into value between 0 and 1)
👉 Step 3: Output probability

code(explanation):
taking iris Dataset ~ data(iris)
iris$IsSetosa ~ it means we are creating a new column for species that actually is

ifelse(iris$Species=="setosa",1,0) ~ a filtering process that take only setosa as 1 and everything else 0 to newly created column
model <- glm(IsSetosa ~ Petal.Length, data=iris, family=binomial) ~ Predict IsSetosa using Petal.Length

glm = generlised linear model(better search it online for further understanding 
family = binomial ~ basically telling R to take logistic regression

plot(iris$Petal.Length, iris$IsSetosa) ~ X-axis → Petal Length ,Y-axis → IsSetosa (0 or 1)
curve(predict(model, data.frame(Petal.Length=x), type="response"), add=TRUE) ~
                              What happens here:
                                    predict() computes probability from the model

                                    type="response" gives probability values (0–1)

                                    curve() draws the logistic function

                                    add=TRUE overlays it on the existing plot
                              

